  	    "description": "Miami native Karen Russell is a novelist, writing professor, sometimes GQ correspondent, and, now, a certified, undeniable genius. Maybe you heard. Last month, when the MacArthur Foundation announced its twenty-four \u0022Genius\u0022 grants, our young...",
  	    "articleBody": "FacebookPinterest\u000A\u000AMiami native Karen Russell is a novelist, writing professor, sometimes GQ correspondent, and, now, a certified, undeniable genius. Maybe you heard. Last month, when the MacArthur Foundation announced its twenty-four &amp;#x201C;Genius&amp;#x201D; grants, our young Brooklynite was on the list. Her writings &amp;#x201C;blend fantastical elements with psychological realism and classic themes of transformation and redemption,&amp;#x201D; said the committee. &amp;#x201C;She depicts in lyrical, energetic prose an enchanting and forbidding landscape and delves into subcultures rarely encountered in contemporary American literature.&amp;#x201D;\u000A\u000A(And not to honk our own horn here, but Russell is the second GQer to land a MacArthur. Correspondent George Saunders [whom she cites as an influence] was awarded Genius status in 2006.)\u000A\u000AContacted the day after, Russell was still in shock and (she said) not ready for any sort of a press conference. But after some time, a bit of pleading, and the Breaking Bad series finale, Ms. 305 agreed to a morning interview that became an afternoon interview after she forgot her cell phone.\u000A\u000AGQ: When and where did you get the Call?\u000A\u000A Karen Russell: I got the call on a Wednesday, right at dusk. I came back to my studio and there was a call from a weird area code on my voicemail; given the freakily unfamiliar area code, I assumed it was from my car insurance company. My car was stolen last month, and I&amp;#x2019;ve spent time on the phone with &amp;#x201C;Monica&amp;#x201D; the insurance adjustor. The woman on my voicemail was &amp;#x201C;Cecilia,&amp;#x201D; not &amp;#x201C;Monica,&amp;#x201D; but she spoke in a tone of professional friendliness and authority, which is basically the USAA tone. I thought about letting it go, but I didn&amp;#x2019;t want trouble with USAA.\u000A\u000ADid you know the Foundation was looking your way?\u000A\u000A I truly had no idea. No one can apply, and no one knows they are being considered. I could not be more grateful—I&amp;#x2019;m still shell-shocked, I think. On their website they say, &amp;#x201C;The award is speculative; it does not recognize lifetime achievement but invests in individual potential.&amp;#x201D; And it feels really wonderful, to think that these seasoned gamblers at the MacArthur are going to bet on you and your work.\u000A\u000ADid you call back or let it go?\u000A\u000A I called back, standing in this foreign kitchen, on week two of my Brooklyn tenancy, and Cecilia [Conrad, VP of the MacArthur Fellows program] asked me if I knew about the MacArthur Grant. A friend of mine had just been joking, when R. Kelly dropped sex &amp;#x201C;Genius,&amp;#x201D; that R. Kelly should get the MacArthur.\u000A\u000AThen what?\u000A\u000A Cecilia told me the details of the award, but not before I did the Price is Right reaction. I was like &amp;#x201C;No no no no.&amp;#x201D; Then I learned I was on speakerphone. There was a room full of people listening in. These people comprised the MacArthur Selection Committee. Then I started breathing like a fat man on a trampoline, and babbling my thanks. I think I avoided expletives, but I can&amp;#x2019;t be certain. &amp;#x201C;Happy&amp;#x201D; is too simple a modifier for my feelings upon receipt of this baffling, surreal, hilariously great news.\u000A\u000ADon&amp;#x2019;t they make you wait a week or something?\u000A\u000A They let you tell one person, but I cheated a little bit and told my brother and sister. I wanted to tell them both at once, but I couldn&amp;#x2019;t get Gchat to show both their faces. When I told them, they kept me grounded by listing one hundred of the dumbest things I&amp;#x2019;ve ever said and done. Then my brother cranked DJ Laz, in tribute to Miami. It&amp;#x2019;s a tricky Miss Manners situation, it&amp;#x2019;s hard to know how to celebrate an impossible moment like that, on Gchat.\u000A\u000ADo you get a pin or a medal or some plaque or something?\u000A\u000A It would be great if you got a brass &amp;#x201C;M&amp;#x201D; breastplate, or a scepter of some kind that would visually establish you as a non-dummy, and maybe translate into subway seats and free drinks, but I don&amp;#x2019;t think you get anything material. (What you do get is so mind-bogglingly generous that I am still in gratitude-anaphylactic shock). Even without MacArthur armor or a monogrammed sweater, I am so honored.\u000A\u000AWhat were your first sober thoughts?\u000A\u000A Right away I was converting the money into time. Time that I can dedicate to writing. I hope to write more non-fiction for you guys, but at the moment I&amp;#x2019;m back to imaginary worlds. I like fictionland. There&amp;#x2019;s no fact-checking there and it&amp;#x2019;s not an ethical breach to swap in new settings and rearrange chronologies and shape your characters&amp;#x2019; dialogue. So even though writing a new story is always a struggle for me, at least in fictionland I&amp;#x2019;m less likely to be sued.\u000A\u000AHow will this award affect you as a writer?\u000A\u000A I also love the use of that word &amp;#x201C;speculative&amp;#x201D; to modify the prize, because as a fiction writer, I really do feel that the prize opens up so many new horizons. And at the same time that I feel free to pursue all kinds of wild projects, in fictionland, in our brick-and-mortar everyday, I&amp;#x2019;m just so happy to be able to pay the rent and maybe get a stable home base set up. I&amp;#x2019;ve been in Berlin and then Philly and in January I&amp;#x2019;m going to Iowa, and I just moved into a studio sublet in Brooklyn. Just orbiting the tarmac, trying to land the plane.\u000A\u000AIs there anything bad about getting a half-million dollars for being a genius?\u000A\u000A One immediate consequence of receiving the MacArthur is that I now view the telephone as an almost occult object, a portal through which the most astonishing news manifests itself. Good news! I think that&amp;#x2019;s the surprise, when it&amp;#x2019;s so much easier to expect disaster. The day after I heard from Cecilia, a D.C. area code called, and I laughed, realizing that a part of me now believed anything was possible. Maybe it was Obama. Maybe it was Abraham Lincoln, calling to request stoppage of the Booth assassination. It&amp;#x2019;s going to be a long life now, primed to expect shockingly good news from unknown numbers, when it&amp;#x2019;s much more likely to be a wrong number, somebody calling for their drunk uncle in Hialeah, or demanding stuffed-crust pizza.",
  	    "author": ["Cole Louison"],
  	    "keywords": ["Karen Russell","MacArthur Genius Awards","Pop Culture"]
